metadata.name: cold embrace #26
metadata.description:
'cold embrace' is a depiction of a city embraced by a blizzard. Despite the harshness of a snowstorm, there is beauty to be found in the accumulation of snow atop otherwise bare structures.

Infinite variations guarantee a unique scene. 
4 colour palettes of varying rarities.

800x800
100% made with code (using p5.js).

metadata.name: Ephemeral Fountain v1.0 #106
metadata.description:
This project originated with me thinking about how to do very realistic glass spheres that can be manipulated and moved within the THREE.js environment. Mixing that with several hundred ephemeral non-glass objects which are moving in a fountain-like flow, adding reflection and refraction to the glass, and combining it all in a physical existence which I playfully only impose on the non-glass objects nearby... in this world, glass can move through glass, with interesting effects similar to diamonds firing when light hits them at just the right angle! 

Extremely rare to get 8 glass spheres... By the randomness imposed, 30% will have one sphere, 30% two, 20% three, 10% four, 5% five, 3% six, 1% seven and 1% eight. Happy hunting!

metadata.name: The Past Ahead #253
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

metadata.name: Temporal Black #64
metadata.description:
"Temporal Black" is a free (giveaway) collection for the holders of initial "Temporal" drop https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/22849

A gift for the change of year.


"Temporal Black" is a generative (pure code) artwork of abstract colored geometric shapes and forms, mixed in a way that trying to simulate natural media

Technically, colored shapes and curves are drawn in a graphic buffer and my custom fragment shader process and transforms the buffer content into that noisy and scratched output. All are 100% code, no images used.


CONTROLS

KEYS:

- 1-4: Set resolution from 1x to 4x of the current dimension (possibly slower performance in higher values)
- S: Save a png file with the current resolution

- P: Change orientation to Portrait with aspect ratio 0.75 (useful eg. for printing)
- L: Change orientation to Landscape with ratio 4/3  (1.333..)
- O: Change orientation to Square (box)
  Due to some 1:1 ratio sensitive calculations, rendering output may differ when switching orientations

----
Made with p5js and custom shaders

ABOUT THE ARTIST
Want to know more ? please read the "SHORT BIO" section here in "Emotions" collection: https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/22243

metadata.name: Fragment of Time #165
metadata.description:
"Year" is a mere four-letter word. But in reality, much has occurred. There are 12 months or approximately 365 days in a year. I joined fxhash about 4 months ago. And a lot has happened in my life since then. Can you imagine what happened to the people who founded, participated in, and maintained fxhash from its founding days? Everyday must've been different, and each day has its own pattern and color.

I've felt as if I lived in two different worlds since joining fxhash. I'm an architect by day, and a creator by night. I'm a part of fxhash, and I believe every single one of us experiences it that way. Each day has its own pattern and color.

This piece is my way of imagining what this community has gone through in a year. Each block represents a month from November 2021 to October 2022, with every block consists of smaller blocks that represents a day. Each of these days have their own colors and patterns. Every day tells its own story. But when you imagine a bigger picture of what happened in a year, you will see a specific pattern and color that you can keep as one big composition, and that gives you a year full of stories to admire.

I try to participate in the anniversary event as a way of expressing my gratitude. For everyone who has helped build this community so vibrant and meaningful - you have created such a world, and subsequently made my year. And therefore to me, you are all wonderful souls. So many artists, collectors, coders, art enthusiasts, and all of fxhash's teams have inspired me. Don't stop creating awesome stuff. Happy Birthday fxhash!!

metadata.name: Element #9
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Kumano (Emergent Structures 1) #87
metadata.description:
"Kumano (Emergent Structures 1)" is a collection of generative works that emulate analog effects from painting, printmaking, and textile design. It is the first generative collection in a continuing series called Emergent Structures.

The title of this collection is borrowed from Kumano-zome (ÁÜäÈáéÊüì„ÇÅ), a traditional Japanese craft of resist-dyed fabric that creates beautiful analog interference patterns (moir√©). These textiles, often rendered in tones of indigo dye, date back at least two hundred years, and yet they can feel magically modern. 

The primary structure of "Kumano" is a mesh of overlapping angled lines that function just like the hand-printed lines in Kumano-zome textiles.

My background is in abstract painting, and one of my goals for this collection was to create an abstract "painting space" and develop a painterly visual language, and then treat the outputs like I would treat a running series of paintings; exploring and working through all the ideas, within certain constraints, trying to exhaust every possibility.

I wanted the outputs to look like they were created by hand, with soft edges and manual imperfections. Colors are deliberately "mis-registered" and shapes/lines are subtly askew. The "Viscosity" feature turns emergent moir√© patterns into flattened, solid forms, and renders them as if they were painted with watercolors, or stamped with bleeding inks.


The composition of each piece is mostly determined by five main components:

1. Layers of repeating lines at various angles and spacing, which often overlap and interact to create complex moir√© patterns (Kumano Layers)

2. A "Horizon" section that creates a foreground space and a horizon line, bringing the piece into a painterly landscape space

3. Bold caution stripes of various color, thickness, opacity, and orientation

4. Floating "Satellite" shapes that sometimes appear, evoking moons or man-made objects hovering in space

5. A special mix of "Viscosity" and "Erosion" that makes the paint bleed, congeal, and dissolve in unpredictable ways


The overarching color story of each piece is determined by a few interrelated palettes:

- Ten possible Background Colors
- Eight possible palettes for the layered lines (Kumano Palette)
- Eight possible colors of Caution Stripes
- Six possible colors for the Horizon/Foreground layer

When applied in combination and then run through the Viscosity and/or Erosion filters, the breadth of color possibilities is enormous, but always remains connected and coherent.


The algorithm's compositional structure also shows extreme variety, from highly complex to super clean, minimal, and subtle. Everything in the artwork is generated directly from the p5.js script; no external inputs, filters, or images are used.


These pieces are best viewed at large scale in order to appreciate the fine details and nuance. To save a high-res version, just type "S" on your keyboard and a high-res PNG will be generated and downloaded. This can take some time, so please be patient while it renders in the background. In most browsers the high-res output will be 5000 x 6250px (31+ megapixels).
